Background

*Melanie Perkins, welcome to Stratechery.*

*Melanie Perkins:* Thank you so much for having me. Excited to be here.

*So we=E2=80=99re here to talk about Canva and your journey towards leading=
 one of the most valuable private companies in the world. But while there a=
re a few profiles of you that start with the beginning of your entrepreneur=
ial journey in your college years, I want to go back further. Tell me what =
it was like growing up in Perth, Australia. That is on Planet Earth, right?=
 Just to confirm.*

*MP:* It is, yeah. I believe it=E2=80=99s actually one of the most isolated=
 cities in the world. Bizarrely, I chose to do ice skating growing up, whic=
h was definitely an atypical thing to be doing in Perth, Australia.

*I was going to ask you about the ice skating actually. Are there any lesso=
ns in training to be an ice skater that ends up having being useful for ent=
repreneurship?*

*MP:* Oh, absolutely. I think probably one of the primary ones is when you=
=E2=80=99re learning something new, you fall down hundreds of times, if not=
 thousands, and you have to keep on getting up and trying again and trying =
again and I feel like that same approach is definitely what is required for=
 entrepreneurship.

*So how legitimate was this scarf business you supposedly also started when=
 you were a kid?*

*MP:* I=E2=80=99m impressed! You=E2=80=99ve done your research. So it was a=
 very small business, I think I started when I was 15 and I made some scarv=
es, and I took them to women=E2=80=99s boutiques and sold them and it was a=
 very great learning experience for me because firstly, I had to make somet=
hing of value. I had to overcome my fears and go and speak to shop assistan=
ts and see if they were interested in stocking my scarves. So it definitely=
 wasn=E2=80=99t a booming business, but it definitely taught me a lot of le=
ssons.

*Yeah, my experience, my daughter is pretty entrepreneurial as well, is tha=
t teenage entrepreneurs do a very poor job of valuing their own time, and s=
o they think they=E2=80=99re making more money than they are. Did that char=
acterize your scarf business?*

*MP:* Yeah, I=E2=80=99d say if you were to actually count the hours that I =
put into the scarves compared to the returns, it probably wasn=E2=80=99t gr=
eat. But considering I didn=E2=80=99t really value my time all that much an=
d making a couple hundred dollars each year with each shop was super worthw=
hile for me.

*Was the scarves, was that the end of the figure skating career or were you=
 doing both at the same time?*

*MP:* Actually, interesting point. I think that my ice skating career may h=
ave been starting to wind down as my scarf business was picking up.

*That makes sense, it sounds like a lot to do at the same time. So the firs=
t business you started with your business partner and now husband Cliff Obr=
echt ( https://x.com/cliffobrecht ) was called Fusion Books. Tell me about =
that.*

*MP:* I was at university, I was teaching design programs that were super h=
ard and complex, and I thought they should be all online and simple and col=
laborative. But rather than trying to tackle that entire very large market =
right at the start, we decided to tackle school yearbooks in Australia.

So while we were studying, just started this business, got software develop=
ed by a company in Perth that very kindly did it at a very cheap rate. That=
 meant that the small loan that we had was able to cover the first round of=
 development, but then we had to get profitable really quickly because we h=
ad no more funding available. We did that for a number of years, and each y=
ear, we invested all the profits back into the business and became one of t=
he largest yearbook companies in Australia.

*So this is where you would have software for high school classes and it wa=
s explicitly designed for your =E2=80=94 was this an actual application or =
was that web software?*

*MP:* Yeah, it was web software. So the whole school could log in, create t=
heir profile pages. You could actually lay out your article pages, your pho=
to pages, and it was actually very much a similar vein to what we eventuall=
y have brought to Canva.

*Well, that=E2=80=99s my question. What=E2=80=99s the honest order of opera=
tions here? Was it that you had the vision of Canva and started with your b=
ooks, which would be impressive, or is that you saw an opportunity and then=
 you backed out and say, =E2=80=9CWow, this could be a broader tool=E2=80=
=9D?*

*MP:* Actually, my first business plan was much more encompassing, I wanted=
 to go a lot further. It was quite a long business plan, and I spoke to an =
accountant. They were like, =E2=80=9CYou probably shouldn=E2=80=99t try to =
do all of that at the same time=E2=80=9D.

*What was it? What was the big business plan?*

*MP:* I was going to be doing photo books and this and that, and all sorts =
of things, and then brought it to school yearbooks, which I guess I didn=E2=
=80=99t believe that we could do the full thing, but it became more apparen=
t and more apparent that that was going to be the future. In 2011, I wrote =
actually what I called The Future of Publishing and it was talking about th=
e full industry. Whether or not we could do that was definitely a huge ques=
tion, but it was very apparent to me that that was the future, whether or n=
ot we had the ability or rights to do that was a different question.

The Future of Publishing

*Well, now I fell short, I did not find the Future of Publishing, tell me a=
bout it. What was the thesis?*

*MP:* I can send it to you if you would like a good bedtime reading.

*I will link it in the interview! [ Editor=E2=80=99s Note: the essay is not=
 online. ] What=E2=80=99s the two minute synopsis?*

*MP:* The two minute synopsis was =E2=80=94 do you want me to read you a li=
ttle passage from it? It was kind of funny.

*Sure, go ahead.*

*MP:* =E2=80=9CThe Future of Publishing. The era of desktop publishing as w=
e know it is coming to an end, and the world is now ready for a market lead=
er to emerge =E2=80=94 perhaps a small, versatile company that knows the ma=
rket well, intimately well, is in a better position to take the reins of th=
is unbridled market.=E2=80=9D It was quite dramatic, and went on.

*Don=E2=80=99t worry. When I was in college, I wrote very dramatically as w=
ell. I can relate.*

*MP:* And we weren=E2=80=99t yet into really succinct business plans. This =
was pitch decks, this was very much a extensive business plan, and it was t=
alking about how fast Internet and the spread of social networks and the in=
filtration of digital cameras and smartphones and tablets was all coming to=
gether to create this extraordinary opportunity and that we had a bit of ex=
perience with Fusion Books and we wanted to take on this huge market.

*So what opened your eyes to this? Again, it=E2=80=99s quite remarkable. Yo=
u look back thirteen years, and 1) you were right, and 2) you are building =
that company. So what gave you that insight at that stage of life?*

*MP:* I think that was continuous learnings. The learnings from teaching th=
e design programs and seeing students struggle with it at the same time as =
jumping onto social media networks at the time and not having to go and lea=
rn for a long time. I think that vantage point, teaching design programs =
=E2=80=94 and at my university, you do communications across science and ar=
ts, and each of the different specialties would have to go and learn these =
things.

I was seeing how important digital communications was at the same time as h=
ow hard it was to adopt those things, I think was extremely critical in my =
learning, and also because I was teaching all of these different design pro=
grams. It=E2=80=99d be things like Photoshop and InDesign, and then a diffe=
rent program for video creation and a different program, Dreamweaver for we=
bsites, and that also seemed really archaic because why should you have to =
learn a new program every time you want to design something new?

So there were a lot of realizations, I think through that teaching aspect, =
and then a lot of learnings, I guess through Fusion Books as well. So every=
 time we talk to a customer, we=E2=80=99d actually give them a 30-minute ph=
one tutorial and so we got a really strong sense of how they interacted wit=
h our programs, what made sense, what didn=E2=80=99t make sense, so just co=
ntinuous learning really.

*Is this a realization that a 30-year-old or a 40-year-old could have had, =
or was it really critical that you were in your early 20s and looking at th=
e world with fresh eyes?*

*MP:* I think that helped. I think there was definitely no knowledge of wha=
t was or should have been, and I wasn=E2=80=99t anchored to the old way of =
doing things in any way whatsoever, I just wanted my students to be able to=
 do it easier. But anyone could have a realization, I think I was in a fort=
unate position to be able to have those learnings through those experiences=
.

Starting Canva

*How did you decide to give up Fusion Books and do Canva? Was it that you h=
ad this vision in mind and you realized that you had started down that path=
, but now you were sort of in a box? What was the decision point there?*

*MP:* So an investor from Silicon Valley, Bill Tai ( https://x.com/KiteVC )=
 , came to Perth, and I spoke to him for five minutes after the WA Inventor=
 of the Year Competition Luncheon, and he said that if I went to San Franci=
sco, he=E2=80=99d be happy to meet with me. So I jumped on a plane to say, =
after him ignoring my emails a few times, I said I was going to be in the n=
eighborhood, and then went to the most nerve-wracking meeting of my life in=
 San Francisco and pitched The Future of Publishing, and that was where I a=
ctually created a lot of these decks.

We were still running Fusion Books, in fact, Cliff, my co-founder and husba=
nd, wasn=E2=80=99t at the time, boyfriend at the time, he was running Fusio=
n Books, and I was trying to tackle this, =E2=80=9CHow do we get Canva star=
ted?=E2=80=9D. Meeting him was like, =E2=80=9COh my gosh, there=E2=80=99s a=
 whole world out there=E2=80=9D, we didn=E2=80=99t know anything about star=
tups or this whole ecosystem.

*There=E2=80=99s a lot of framing in some of these profiles that I read abo=
ut the advantage of being in Australia, being away from Silicon Valley. But=
 what I=E2=80=99m hearing from you is you did need a dash of Silicon Valley=
. You had these huge dreams, this huge vision, and you kind of needed a bit=
 of that going to a place that is like, usually if you=E2=80=99re a VC inve=
stor that wants a grand slam, you=E2=80=99re pushing your startup founders =
to think larger. It sounds like they that wasn=E2=80=99t a problem for you,=
 you just needed someone to let you know that that was possible.*

*MP:* Yeah, I think that we=E2=80=99ve really benefited from having the bes=
t of both worlds. I think there=E2=80=99s been an incredible number of adva=
ntages of being able to build the company in Australia primarily. Now, we=
=E2=80=99ve now got offices and campuses all around the world, but I think =
there=E2=80=99s been a huge amount of benefit from that. But then also bein=
g able to go into Silicon Valley, meet lots of amazing people, get inspired=
, and I think know that it=E2=80=99s possible. So it is kind of all well an=
d good having these ideas, but that is the future, but the=E2=80=94

*The validation is important.*

*MP:* Yeah! And I guess living in Perth in Australia, I didn=E2=80=99t real=
ly that people could build products. I know that might sound a bit bizarre,=
 but it wasn=E2=80=99t until I met Lars Rasmussen ( https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Lars_Rasmussen_(software_developer) ) , who co-founded Google Maps, =
that I realized, =E2=80=9COh, normal people that are nice and hardworking c=
an actually build these products rather than just be consumers of them=E2=
=80=9D, so I think that that was a really important unlock for me when I we=
nt to Silicon Valley for the first time.

*And Lars is the one that pushed you to hire [Canva Co-Founder and Chief Pr=
oduct Officer] Cameron Adams ( https://mastodon.cloud/@themaninblue ) , rig=
ht?*

*MP:* When we met for the first time, we connected and we chatted about all=
 these big lofty ideas, and he said he=E2=80=99d be my tech advisor, but wh=
at that meant was him saying to me for a year that the people that I was br=
inging to the table weren=E2=80=99t the right ones and then he introduced m=
e to Cam, and he also introduced me to Dave Hearnden ( https://www.linkedin=
.com/in/david-hearnden-5550541/ ) , who became our CTO. So he really realiz=
ed that to build the things that we wanted to build, we had to have an incr=
edible tech team and despite the fact that felt quite frustrating at the ti=
me because he kept on saying I couldn=E2=80=99t have the people that I want=
ed, and I was so itching to get started, it did mean that we had a really s=
olid tech foundation and team to be able to build this very gigantic vision=
 that we had.

*Well, I take it you now agree that he was right.*

*MP:* He was totally right, yes. Definitely right.

*How important is this balance? Because I think Silicon Valley, to this bit=
 about the balance between Australia and Silicon Valley, Silicon Valley is =
probably over-indexed on the technical founder, and what I already get from=
 you, and I got this from the profiles before, is this clarity of vision an=
d this ability to create something completely new, which, to be frank, tech=
nical co-founders are not always the strongest at. It sounds like this is a=
nother example of you needed to get the best of both worlds to sort of pull=
 this off.*

*MP:* Yeah, I couldn=E2=80=99t agree more. I think because out of necessity=
, I really had to get extreme clarity of vision because I was getting rejec=
ted by so many investors, which meant I had to be able to articulate it rea=
lly well and really succinctly and not read my 26 page deck plan. I had to =
get in a really short, succinct pitch. But also just having that real world=
 experience solving real problems, I think also was a real advantage becaus=
e I think if you get funded really quickly and easily, you kind shortcut a =
lot of that, I think, quite important learning.

*Did you have a lot of frustration dealing with a hired tech team for Fusio=
n Books, or did you not even realize the possibilities of having your own c=
rack team?*

*MP:* Oh, I loved working with our dev teams when we were hiring the develo=
pment companies. In fact, I think that was a really advantageous thing actu=
ally, because I really got to hone the ideas. The first team I worked with,=
 they laugh about it, but I=E2=80=99d come in each week with my 30 page rev=
